Preparing for Exercises 2-5

For the next exercises I first set the data frame to nc.

data = nc

Then I use ggplot to create a scatterplot of weeks on x axis and weight on y axis to explore the relationship between pregnancy length and birth weight.

ggplot(data = nc, aes(x=weeks, y = weight)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs( x = "Pregnancy Length (weeks)", y = "Birth Weight of Newborn (pounds)", title = "Relationship between Pregnancy Length and Birth Weight")

Exercise 2

There is a positive relationship between the length of pregnancy and newborns birth weight. As pregnancy lengths increase, birth weights increase.

Exercise 3

For this exercise I will create and run a code to graph pregnancy length in weeks on the x-axis and weight gained by the pregnant person on the y-axis.

ggplot(data = nc, aes(x=weeks, y = gained)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs( x = "Pregnancy Length (weeks)", y = "Weight Gained in Pregnancy (pounds)", title = "Relationship between Pregnancy Length and Weight Gained During Pregnancy by Pregnant Persons")

Exercise 4

Next I will add a new argument in the above code to indicate values that correspond with a premature birth weight.

ggplot(data = nc, aes(x=weeks, y = gained, color = premie)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs( x = "Pregnancy Length (weeks)", y = "Weight Gained in Pregnancy (pounds)", title = "Pregnancy Length and Weight Gained During Pregnancy by Pregnant Persons")

  1. The argument color = premie added colors to data points to distinguish between values with full term versus premature newborn birth weights.

  2. Three variables are now displayed, which are premie, weeks, and gained. Premie can be thought of as a binary categorical variable.

  3. 36 (and a quarter) weeks is the rough cutoff for when a baby is considered full term or premature. Greater than ~36 is considered full term; less than or equal to ~36 is premature.

Exercise 5

For this exercise I created a new scatterplot showing mage on the x-axis and birth weight on the y-axis. The plot also includes color based on the newborns sex.

ggplot(data = nc, aes(x=mage, y = weight, color = gender)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs( x = "Pregnant Persons' Age (years)", y = "Birth Weight of Newborns (pounds)", title = "Pregnant Persons' Age, Newborn Sex, and Birth Weight of Newborns")

There is not a strong relationship between maternal age and birth weight. Babies that weigh over six pounds seem to have similar frequency between ages 20 and 40, which are also the ages people tend to have children. Below is a second plot showing maternal age, birt hweight of newborns, and premature status.

Preparing for Exercises 6 and 7.

In this section I am using histograms to explore distributions of single numerical values. Ill start with pregnancy duration.

ggplot(data = nc, aes(x=weeks)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Next I will change bindwidth and colors on the graph.

ggplot(data = nc, aes(x = weeks)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, color = "white", fill = "steelblue")

Exercise 6

  1. The value being counted is weeks pregnant across each person. So for example, about 130 people had a pregnancy length of 40 weeks.
  2. The distribution seems symmetrical so the average length of pregnancy is around 38 or 39 weeks.
  3. If binwidth were changed to 100 there would be 1 bin with all 800 observations.The histogram below demonstrates how as binwidth increases the distribution of observations becomes less clear and more observations are placed in fewer bins.
ggplot(data = nc, aes(x = weeks)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 25, color = "white", fill = "steelblue")

Exercise 7

#### Preparing for Exercise 8

ggplot (data = nc, aes(x = weeks)) +

Exercise 8

The next histogram will show newborn birth weight split by the newborns sex.

ggplot (data = nc, aes(x = weight)) +

  labs(title = "Frequency of Newborn Birth Weights among Male and Female Newborns")

Females seem to have a slightly larger average birth weight.

Exercise 10

ggplot(data = nc, aes(x = habit, y = weeks)) +

Smokers have more variability than nonsmokers. Their IQR is larger and the tail above the 75th quartile is longer.

Exercise 13

I will use a scatterplot to assess if maternal age and duration of pregnancy have a relationship.

ggplot(data = nc, aes(x=mage, y = weeks)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
  labs( x = "Pregnant Persons' Age (years)", y = "Pregnancy Duration (weeks)", title = "Pregnant Persons' Age and Pregnancy Duration")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The scatterplot shows a slightly negative relationship between a persons age and pregnancy duration. As age increases the duration of pregnancy decreases slightly. The slope of the line is not a large magnitude and many points fall above and below so it is a very week association based on this plot.

Question 1

I viewed the data using View in the console.

Question 2

I used the help function to view descriptions of the variables.

?txhousing

Listings describes total active listings.

Question 3

I will write a chunk to remove the inventory variable and save the results in a dataframe called txhousing.

txhousing <- txhousing |> select(-inventory)

There are now 8 variables instead of 9.

Question 4

I will now make a data set called dallas_sub with only data from 2012 and 2013.

dallas_sub <- txhousing |> filter(year == 2012 | year == 2013, city == "Dallas")

There are 24 observations across 8 variables for Dallas in years 2012 and 2013 (remember that the inventory variable was removed in an earlier chunk).

Question 5

I will add a column to the dallas_sub data with a new variable for percentage of listings that were sold.

dallas_sub <- dallas_sub |> mutate(prct_sold = sales/listings * 100)

There are now 9 variables in the Dallas data set.

Question 6

Now I will calculate the average percent of listings sold in Dallas grouped by month and save the results in a data frame called dallas_summary.

dallas_summary <- dallas_sub |> group_by(month) |> summarize(prct_sold = mean(prct_sold))

Question 7

txhousing |>  
  filter(year == 2012 | year == 2013, city == "Dallas") |> 
  mutate(prct_sold = sales/listings *100) |> 
  group_by(month) |> 
  summarize(mean_prct_sold = mean(prct_sold)) |> 
  arrange(desc(mean_prct_sold))
## # A tibble: 12  2
##    month mean_prct_sold

##  9     9           31.8
## 10    11           30.6
## 11     2           23.5
## 12     1           20.5

This code first filtered the Texas housing data by years to include only 2012 and 2013. It also filtered by city to include only data from Dallas. It created a variable called prct_sold and grouped averages of this new variable by month for 2012 and 2013. It arranged the summary data of this new variable in descending order. It is essentially one chunk that contains all the prior steps from questions 4-7.

Question 9
